Good afternoon Rachael, Thank you for your email. We share your concern tha=
t this matter is stagnating. However, from our client=E2=80=99s point of vi=
ew, that is because Tower has scoped works which expressly require Building=
 Consent, but with no allowance

Good afternoon Rachael,

Thank you for your email.

We share your concern that this matter is stagnating. However, from our cli=
ent=E2=80=99s point of view, that is because Tower has scoped works which e=
xpressly require Building Consent, but with no allowance for consent work.

The position you express in your email below is simply repeating the view i=
n Lance=E2=80=99s email from 27 March. That is: Tower says that the repair =
work scoped does not require building consent because Tower says it does no=
t require building consent. You have provided no expert opinion on this oth=
er than saying =E2=80=9CTower believes the scope of works is appropriate=E2=
=80=9D. You have not even provided a reasoned statement of why Tower says P=
rendos is wrong, with specific reference to the Building Act.

Our client has already paid for Prendos to assess ASURNZ=E2=80=99s repair s=
cope, and has provided Prendo=E2=80=99s expert comments on ASURNZ=E2=80=99s=
 scope, which Tower has not engaged with.

We do not think that the logical next step is for Tower to put its insured =
to more cost by requiring her to pay for an alternative repair scope which =
Tower will then ignore, like it is ignoring Prendos=E2=80=99 report. You sa=
y that =E2=80=9Cusually scopes of works are agreed between the parties thro=
ugh discussion=E2=80=9D. We agree. That is why we have attempted to engage =
with Tower=E2=80=99s scope, and have sought expert advice on it which we ha=
ve shared with Tower. We are attempting to enter a dialogue over scope. It =
is not our client who is not engaging in discussion. On that basis, we look=
 forward to seeing ASURNZ=E2=80=99s response on the Prendos report. If that=
 can be accepted, then we can move on.

We share a common interest in this matter being dealt with quickly. However=
, that does not mean that our client must simply ignore her experts and agr=
ee 100% with Tower=E2=80=99s unevidenced beliefs about the scope.

Our client can=E2=80=99t give a preference over cash settlement or Tower ma=
naged repair without knowing what work Tower would undertake. Our client wi=
ll only be able to express a preference once she knows what scope Tower wou=
ld undertake or pay for =E2=80=93 it is not fair to pressure her for a pref=
erence whilst simultaneously acknowledging that the parties disagree about =
scope. Our client=E2=80=99s preference at this point is that Tower works wi=
th her to prepare a scope of works which ensures the repairs will meet the =
Building Code.

Kind regards

[cid:image008.png@01DCD711.4FC61630]
Richard Hargreaves
